A stack data structure is a linear data structure, meaning that it is organized in a single line, with the first element being the topmost and the last element being the bottommost. It is often used to represent a “stack” of items, where new items can be added to the top of the stack and old items can be removed from the bottom.

Here is how a stack data structure works point by point:

1. Definition: A stack is a data structure that consists of a collection of elements, called the stack elements or the stack data, in which the first element is located at the top of the stack and the last element is located at the bottom.

2. Understanding the terminology: The term "top" refers to the first element in the stack, and the term "bottom" refers to the last element in the stack.

3. Elements can be added or removed: A new data item can be added to the top of the stack, while an old item can be removed from the bottom.

4. Stack elements can be accessed only in the order they were added: The elements in a stack can only be accessed or retrieved in the order that they were added to the stack, starting from the top.

5. Only the topmost element can be accessed at a time: Only the topmost element of the stack can be accessed or retrieved at a time, while all the other elements are hidden underneath it.

6. The stack size is constant: The number of elements in a stack data structure is always the same, and it cannot be altered after the stack has been created.

7. Implementation: A stack can be implemented using an array, where the first element of the array is located at the top and the last element is located at the bottom. When a new element is added to the stack, it is pushed onto the end of the array, and when an element is popped off the stack, it is removed from the beginning of the array.

